Illustrative examples of filter transfer functions for a Legendre MRA are shown in figure 1, for 
u=1,3 and 5. A low-pass behaviour is exhibited for the filter H, as expected. The number of zeroes within - \pi &lt; \omega &lt; \pi is equal to the degree of the Legendre polynomial. Therefore, the roll-off of side-lobes with frequency is easily controlled by the parameter 
u.

H_{
u} (\omega)=-e^{-j 
u  rac {\omega - \pi} {2}} P_{
u}( \cos ( rac {\omega} {2}))
The transfer function of the high-pass analysing filter G_{
u} (\omega) is chosen according to Quadrature mirror filter condition [6,7], yielding:

H_{
u} (\omega)=-e^{-j {(
u-2)}  rac {\omega} {2}} P_{
u}( \sin ( rac {\omega} {2}))
Indeed, |G_{
u}(0)|=0 and |G_{
u}( \pi)|=1, as expected.

A suitable phase assignment is done so as to properly adjust the transfer function H_{
u} (\omega) to the form H_{
u} (\omega)=  rac {1} {\sqrt {2}} \sum_{k \in Z} h_k^{
u} e^{-j \omega k}

The filter coefficients \{ h_k \}, k \in Z are given by:  rac {h_k^{
u}} {\sqrt {2}}= -  rac {1} {2^{2 
u}}. inom{2k}{k}. inom{2 
u -2k}{
u -k}

It follows then the symmetry: {h_k^{
